segments.text: Do you happen to remember when Worley sold out?
You know what?
Worley sold out that fellow named Carr lived in Austin.
And Carr sold out.
He sold that land out there to old man Foster.
Old man Foster.
He had a jetty.
And that land all belonged to jetty.
Jetty?
Yeah, a fella by the name of Jetty.
And Old Man Foster married his daughter.
After Old Man Jetty died, you see that Old Man Foster fell out of that land over there in the mine.
And then Old Man Foster got in bad shape and moved to town.
He sold the coffee.
So coffee owns all that out there now.
One thing I noticed,
to get back to the social activities, they said the baseball games were big.
Oh, hell, them Nets can get over there.
The company give them a little land, they can play it all, and they played baseball the other Saturday and Sunday.
Well, were there company baseball teams?
Yeah, there was one company that played the other company.
See, there's several minds.
One company, a baseball player, would come and play the other baseball game.
It'd be just like... Did you ever play baseball with them?
Oh, yeah, I played a whole lot.
I didn't work with shit.
Were Mexicans pretty good ballplayers?
They were pretty good, yeah.
Did their wives and kids come out and watch?
Oh, yeah.
When did they usually play these baseball games?
They still have some games here now.
Last year they had a game they played at the fire park up here.
But the mining companies got together?
These boys, they don't...
They're not coal miners anymore, though.
They work for these farmers, you know, and they get together.
These boys live in town and work on these public jobs.
They'd get together, send dogs somewheres, some other town in Michigan to come from other towns to play them, just like they do with these big ball games, you know.
They'd come to other places, and they'd have games.
The best damn players I ever seen was a damned old nigger.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
But he wasn't with mine, so.
No.
Well, I cannot put my finger on what date we were talking about.
Do you remember that?
I wasn't married then.
I was single.
My daddy was one.
See, my daddy was a, he had pneumonia.
And Herman Vogel was running the engine and my daddy and I was working under him.
They had a big hole in the boiler and they were waiting for a boiler repair.
And it was on our last flat to load out.
The boiler split right half in two.
One of them back in went out and the other went all over the damn country to find bricks.
They had bricks, you know.
We had them bricks all over.
You could find them three or four miles from there, where that boiler blowed up and blowed them bricks up.
The damn timber fell on my head over there.
They had a tween wall between the boiler and the engine.
And me and the engine there was a...
It covered us up.
It hadn't been for that inside wall over here that killed us.
It just caved it over on us.
And we scrambled out one of them.
Rogel didn't get hurt at all.
Two or four fell across my head.
They put three stitches in it.
So you were real lucky.
Yeah.
Let me ask you this.
One thing I've been confused about is that did the coal companies engage in the brick building business also?
No.
See, at Rogel, when they started there, they had brick yards.
And they made brick.
They used the old lignite to burn the brick with.
They had a brickyard down there.
Vogel did.
That's what I thought.
Okay.
And he used the lignite to fuel the...
They used the old lignite.
Did you work on that at all?
I never did work.
Well, that's where I started.
I started the brickyard when I was 16 years old.
15, 20 cents an hour.
Then after the brickyard, they stayed there a long time.
They had niggers work the brickyard.
Them goddamn niggers like that.
They had these little wheel boys loaded up full of bricks.
They'd have these running.
They'd load them bricks them days in boxcars.
Sometimes they'd load four or five boxcars of bricks a day.
Shipped them to different places.
I'll go down there and show you where that old brickyard used to be.
There's all that brick there.
It's down there by the old Bogle mine?
Mm-hmm.
Well, we might do that, you know, if you feel like it sometimes.
You ever see one of them bricks?
Okay, could you go back over how they made the bricks again?
You said they made some sort of clay?
They had these, they had mules them days and them slips, you know, the scraper, you used to call them scrapers.
That was a harness on to the... Yeah.
Had mules in those days.
They didn't have no such thing as trucks or nothing like that.
Yeah.
And they had these big outfits that they loaded this clay in.
They'd dump it.
It had a big old outfit that goes around, goes plumb around.
And they'd dump that clay in there.
And they had belts to carry this, and they'd dump it in the press.
And that press would work up and down, four bricks at a time.
Four bricks at a time?
Four bricks at a time.
And there'd be a man out there that loaded in these wheelbars.
They'd be raw bricks, but they'd be pressed enough that they wouldn't come apart.
Right.
And they'd haul them and put them in them burners.
In a burner?
In them burners, and then burn the brick.
And when they come out, that's when they load them in there.
I see.
And they used the lignite to fire the burners.
They fired the burners.
There was...
They had little old openings.
They had the cast-on outfits in them.
They had these bow and burners, you know, grates, late-night grates.
They'd put that in and they'd say, well, these are about that long.
And these long keels, and they'd get them, that raw brick in there, these long keels over there, and there'd be one
About every foot there'd be one of them openings where you put the lignite in.
On both sides, on the north side and south side.
And you'd just shovel it in?
Yeah, they'd start to eat it.
You'd smoke them kind of like that about a week.
Then about two weeks after that, they'd put hot fire in there.
And that's what made them.
How long did it take to fire them for?
Well, it'd take them four days.
It'd take them longer to smoke them.
They'd smoke them about two or three weeks.
And they'd get them kind of solid.
And it'd take about eight or ten days before they'd be hard as that.
You were talking earlier that they had a change in the type of lighting system they used in the mines.
What was the first type of lighting system they used?
I guess it'd be back in the 1890s, early 1900s?
Yeah, I bet so.
I don't know when that coal mine started.
It was already running, see, when my daddy came in.
What kind of a light system did they use for the hand?
You said they had a... Well, these lamps, these lamps is all they used.
When they first started, they had these, just like I tell you, little torches.
Little torches?
Just like a lamp.
I see.
There's a stem stuck out that way, and they put the oil on top.
They put oil on them.
They put oil in them.
That oil is just... You've seen these torches that you put on the highways, you know?
That's the way they fixed with a wick in them.
I see.
They'd have a wick about...
four or five inches long, they'd stick it down in there, close it up, run it out through that spout, and that oil would keep, they'd have to light them with matches.
They didn't have none like carbide then.
It kept a pocket full of matches.
And that little lamp oil would burn you all day long.
I see.
It was kind of dangerous though, wasn't it, when the oil spilled?
Well, all it would do is get your head green.
But one thing about it, when there was something wrong in there and wasn't good, them lamps wouldn't burn.
If you went in one black, in a black damp or something in there, you better not go in there.
When that light went out, you better not go in there.
That light will let you know not to go in there.
And these carbide lamps, they won't go out.
But when there's black damp over there, that blaze will be that fur, and when you get in that black damp,
It'll come way out here.
That shows you got black damp.
These carbide lamps show you that, too.
Now, this is black damp?
Black damp.
D-A-M-P?
It's where there's no air, you see.
You can get in there and go black damp.
Just like sometimes, you know, people go in the well, they call it black damp.
I see.
You go in there, and if you're in old coal mine, you go in there, and if you're getting black damp, you can smell it.
It smells plum sweet.
I see.
Well, you better down here or not go in there.
Did that happen quite a bit in these mines?
It was once in a while, but they know what it was.
And so they'd get out, and how would they take away the black dam?
They'd open some more out, take it away, and put air in.
They had these engines on the outside, and they had these big propellers, and that would draw that bad air out of there.
I see.
That'd give you air in the coal mines, too, you see.
They opened a little tunnel and they put this fan over there.
It was run by steam.
It was run steaming.
And they'd have wings on them.
You've seen these propellers just like these air-conditioned fans?
Well, it was made kind of like that.
But it was a great big thing.
You know, as big as this house.
And they'd go down in these diggers' outfits where the air could go in there.
And that's what's funnest to marry down in them mines.
I see.
Did you have any sons or daughters yourself when you were married?
I got one daughter.
I got one daughter.
It's the only daughter I got.
I got a stepdaughter and two stepsons.
What did your stepsons do?
Did they follow you?
My stepson, he was in a car wreck and his brain's scattered.
He's in the hospital.
And my daughter lives in Houston, my granddaughter.
And my daughter lives in Bryan.
She married a Bohemian.
You have two stepsons?
Two step-sons and one step-daughter, and then my own daughter.
My wife died in 46.
I never did marry no more.
My kids was all grown when she died.
Did your other step-son become a miner also, or did he do something else?
No, he never did work at the coal mine.
Would you think, Willie, that coal mines would be good for Rockdale?
How do you view the coal mine?
I mean, it was your livelihood from most of your life.
Well, they were good days.
Good days?
Everything was cheap.
Go up there and you can buy a pound of bacon for 15, 20 cents.
Coffee, 25 and 30 cents.
Everything was cheap.
Well, they had these commissaries.
Nearly every one of them had a commissary and they sold groceries.
They'd charge your groceries to you and then when you got a payday, they'd take it off you, off your bill.
What did the commissaries look like?
Well, Dr. Sparks had a great big old commissary when he bought it.
But the other places just had little commissaries.
Well, was Dr. Sparks' commissary a two-story or?
No, it was kind of long, long building, about, looks like about 30, 40 feet long, about...
15, 20 feet wide.
But he kept it well stocked.
He could get anything he couldn't down, all but clothes.
And what mine was Dr. Storys associated with?
The Worley mine?
Worley mine.
Worley?
That's the first one that started there.
Well, did they have counters?
in the commissary or?
Yeah, they had county.
You went over there and you tell them what they want and they'd give you what they want.
You didn't go back and pick up things like you do now.
I see.
They went and got everything for you.
They went and got everything.
You called for what you want and they'd go get it for you.
Put it on the county and put it on your bill.
I see.
They kept a little leisure.
You didn't go help yourself then, didn't they?
I see.
Not like the safe way.
They wouldn't have much left.
Time was good then, but they'd steal everything you had.
I see.
Well, did the Mexican women or the Mexican men go to the commissary to shop?
No, they had some Mexican women.
They had men who worked for them in the commissary.
I see.
No, no, I never did know of any women working at the commissary.
Well, which one of the household?
Would it be the wife or the husband that went and actually bought the food?
The women go by most of it.
See the men be working and the women go by the grocery.
I see.
Did you ever own any land around in Rockville?
No, I didn't own nothing until I bought this place.
I always lived on the other man's land.
When I lived in town, that's where my wife died.
When I moved to Coal Mine, when I moved to town, they sold all them little huts out there when the mines closed.
Them farmers would come in there and they bought them.
When did most of the mines close up to your recollection?
The last mine that was up there was in 33.
Would you say the Depression closed them?
Yeah, there was no sale for the lignite.
Do you ever just sit back and think about those days?
Oh yeah, I wish some of it would come back.
It was a good place.
Yeah, we'd all get together, Bessie and me.
We'd all get together and go to them feasts.
Down there, they'd mess and fix some big old meals for me and my wife.
What kind of food did they serve you?
Oh, man, they'd make these style old pepper stuff.
Everything had pepper in it, but we liked it.
They'd make these cornmeal tortillas and flour tortillas.
Mix it all up.
kill a hog or a cow or something, got there and put him on, have a big, they didn't know what barbecue was them days.

They'd take, you know the way the Minskans barbecued, then they'd take the meat, they'd dig a big hole, wrap it up with thick paper, and put a big tow sack around it, put the fire in that hole and cover it up, and that's the way they barbecued it.
My goodness.
That's good.
That's going right.
It's just as good as anything you ever see.
It'd be just as nice and juicy.
I've seen them set the old cow's head and make a good meal out of them.
Gosh.
There's a big old cow.
I've seen them.
That's pretty good eating.
You know, that cow's bag is white meat.
You get out there and you eat some of that cow's bag.
It is good eating.
Would you say on the whole that
The Mexicans were not able to save money?
Well, they never did make enough to save anything them days.
So if they had relatives back in Mexico, they really couldn't help them out by working.
Yeah.
Every once in a while, they'd take a trip.
They let them go back and forage them days.
It wasn't restricted or whatnot.
They'd go back over there.
I've had two or three chances when they asked me if I wanted to go to Mexico with them, but I never did go.
They said they'd pay my way and everything and see that I got back.
But I never did go.
Mexico's a nice place.
I've been there a couple times.
Yeah.
I've had lots of chances to go.
No, they'd send a message over.
I'd give them four, five, six hundred dollars.
He'd go over the coast.
They had to pay so much to get him out of there, you know, out of Mexico.
Sometimes they'd bring back 25 or 30 Mexicans.
So the mine owners would give... To bring them to the mine, they didn't call.
They must have really been able to trust that.
See, they weren't as strict then as they are now.
Let me...
Okay, they would take a Mexican worker and give him the money, and he would go down to Mexico and bring back... And get him back.
I see.
pay their way back, because they had to pay their way back.
They'd give them four or five hundred dollars to bring them back, pay their way, and it didn't cost them nothing.
The mine owners furnished it.
Just to get them in here to go to work for them.
None of the mine owners or their representatives went down with them.
Would you say that the Mexicans were smuggled in?
No, not then Dave.
Not that I know of.
They'd just go over there and go across.
I don't know whether they paid anything enough, see?
Sometimes they wanted to give the Mexicans four or five hundred dollars to bring the boys back, pay their way.
I guess they let them come back then.
They wasn't as strict in them days.
See, we got a lot of wetbacks over here now.
Swimmed across and all that.
Well, what happened to all the Mexican mining families?
Well, they had some of them went
Dallas, some would go different places on these construction jobs.
They all left that I know of there, but two or three of these old Mexicans left here, and they owned their little old places down there.
They bought these little old shacks.
Four or five of them lived here in town that worked out there.
Do you know their names?
I can't think of them right now.
Well, if you think about it, would you think about
